VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'character wasn\'t reproduced correctly. I also told them to fight, but they just ended up waving hello. Guess the AI is a pacifist after all. However, compared to simply feeding the model a single reference image, it'

[10:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'provides a noticeable improvement in maintaining consistency across characters, clothing, and other visual elements. That said, I also discovered several limitations during testing. So, next, let\'s talk about the pitfalls'

[10:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'you should know before using it. Next, I think this is probably the most important part of this video. What are the actual limits of this model? Because if you only look at the'

[10:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'promotional materials and demos, it almost feels like it can do everything. But once you actually run it inside a local workflow, whether you can still get the same results is another story. When I covered MSR a couple of weeks ago, some viewers pointed out that I'

[10:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'hadn\'t tested enough edge cases. So, this time, I don\'t want to only show successful examples. I want to find out where this model actually performs well and where it starts to break down. Hopefully, this can save you some'

[11:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'testing time and help you avoid a few unnecessary headaches. So, let\'s get straight into it. One, how many elements can it reliably handle? From my own testing, the most stable setup is around four elements total.'

[11:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'One character plus two props [music] plus one background. At this level, the consistency is generally pretty reliable. But once you add a fifth element, it becomes much harder to reproduce'

[11:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'everything accurately. You can still occasionally get good results if the character motion stays simple. But the success rate drops to roughly around one out of 10 attempts. At that point, the time cost usually'

[11:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'isn\'t worth it. Two, keep the motion relatively simple. Since the underlying base model is still LTX 2.3, complex actions remain difficult. Once the motion becomes too aggressive, consistency starts breaking'

[11:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'down no matter how strong the reference setup is. Three, don\'t set the resolution below 720p. LTX 2.3 was trained primarily on video data at 720p and above.'

[12:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'If you generate below that resolution, character consistency drops off quite noticeably. Model selection also matters. For these tests, I\'m using the distilled FP8 model, so everything can run on an 8'

[12:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'GB VRAM GPU. The trade-off is that multi-element support is weaker compared to the dev non-distilled model. If you want better results, you can increase CFG and steps and generate multiple attempts.'

[12:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'But those settings will increase generation time significantly, so you\'ll need to decide whether the quality gain is worth the extra cost. Finally, there\'s also a built-in 4K video upscaler.'

[12:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'You can open this group here and disable the other groups to avoid running out of memory. This group uses Flash VSR. Here you can set the upscale factor. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; For low VRAM systems, I recommend selecting tiny long.'

[13:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
